<TITLE> Banks drive stocks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 9 (bdnews24.com)  Stocks finished marginally higher Thursday amid a buying rush in the last half of trade that drove bank and pharmaceuticals issues up. Indices slumped within half an hour of opening on sell-off but regained pace toward closing to end upbeat. Heavyweight Square Pharma added 0.75 percent to Tk 4974.74 to lead the pharmaceuticals rally. AB Bank, IFIC Bank and Rupali Bank spearheaded the gains in the banking sector. AB Bank surged 10.82 percent to Tk 1441.25 after a slump the previous day. The benchmark DGEN or general index ended slightly up at 2304.20, adding 2.84 points or 0.12 percent. The DSE-20 blue chip index advanced 5.66 points or 0.27 percent to 2061.65. The DSI or all-share price index gained 10.0 points or 0.53 percent to 1897.87, buoyed by a surge in Rupali and IFIC shares. IFIC moved up 9.02 percent to Tk 2288.75 on reports that the government would sell its 8.5 percent stakes. The bank also said it had received over Tk 800 million in proceeds from the sale of its rights in NIB Bank, Pakistan. Expectations of a quick handover to a Saudi Prince Bandar Bin Abdul Rahman Al Saud drove Rupali Bank to end at Tk 1454.25, up 8.04 percent. BRAC Bank gained 0.84 percent to Tk 928. Profit-taking however pushed UCBL shares 4.65 percent down to Tk 3561.50. Power companies closed mixed amid a sell-off of DESCO shares. Power Grid Company of Bangladesh, another heavyweight, rose 0.91 percent to Tk 550.5. Summit Power closed at Tk 1240.50, up 1.61 percent. Depressed by a fall in Lafarge Surma, cement stocks finished lower. Of the issues traded, 103 gained, 90 lost and 16 held steady. Turnover fell to Tk 1.08 billion from Tk 1.21 billion. All the major indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange closed higher amid gains in bank and pharmaceutical stocks. Turnover however fell to Tk 107.50 million from Tk 130.10 million. As many as 42 issues ended higher, 41 went down, and nine remained unchanged. bd
